%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EPerhaps%20it%20was%20for%20this%20subconscious%20reason%20that%20Nehru%20was%20seldom%20more%20pleased%20than%20when%20he%20was%20lampooned%20by%20cartoonists%20like%20Shankar%2C%20master%20of%20the%20graphic%20art%20of%20mimicry.%20By%20mimicking%20the%20V-P%2C%20the%20MP%20far%20from%20belittling%20him%2C%20was%20implicitly%20acknowledging%20the%20former%E2%80%99s%20eminence.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20term%20mimic%2C%20as%20noun%20or%20verb%2C%20is%20derived%20from%20the%20Greek%20word%20for%20imitation%2C%20%E2%80%98mimesis%E2%80%99%2C%20which%20itself%20comes%20from%20%E2%80%98mimos%E2%80%99%2C%20imitator%20or%20actor.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EIn%20ancient%20Greece%2C%20mimesis%20was%20the%20foundation%20stone%20of%20all%20art%2C%20from%20poetry%20and%20drama%20to%20sculpture.%20In%20%3Cem%3EThe%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Cem%3ERepublic%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20Plato%20distinguishes%20between%20mimesis%20and%20diegesis%2C%20which%20is%20narration.%20Think%20of%20the%20two%2C%20one%20as%20a%20novel%2C%20a%20fictive%20imagination%20of%20events%2C%20and%20the%20other%20as%20a%20diary%2C%20a%20recording%20of%20real%20happenings.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EMimesis%20was%20central%20to%20Aristotle%E2%80%99s%20%3Cem%3EPoetics%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20in%20which%20imitation%20of%20nature%20and%20the%20natural%20world%20was%20the%20basis%20of%20all%20literary%20creativity.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EAristotle%20deemed%20literature%2C%20to%20which%20both%20tragedy%20and%20comedy%20belong%2C%20to%20be%20more%20educative%20than%20history%2C%20as%20history%20deals%20with%20specific%20facts%20while%20literature%20is%20at%20liberty%20to%20roam%20the%20imaginary%20and%20imaginative%20realm%20of%20what%20might%20have%20been%2C%20as%20an%20imitation%20or%20mimicry%20of%20restrictive%20reality.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ECommentators%20and%20interpreters%20of%20the%20mimetic%20include%20Samuel%20Taylor%20Coleridge%2C%20Sigmund%20Freud%2C%20Jacques%20Derrida%2C%20Iris%20Murdoch%2C%20and%20mythologist%20Roberto%20Calasso.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EIn%20his%20%3Cem%3ETradition%20and%20the%20Individual%20Talent%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20T.S.%20Eliot%20said%20that%20all%20creative%20writers%2C%20consciously%20or%20otherwise%2C%20reflect%20and%20echo%2C%20or%20mimic%20if%20you%20like%2C%20those%20who%20have%20preceded%20them.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EA%20Milton%20would%20not%20have%20been%20a%20Milton%20without%20a%20preceding%20Shakespeare%2C%20nor%20for%20that%20matter%2C%20a%20T.S.%20Eliot%20a%20T.S.%20Eliot%E2%80%A6%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EEliot%20was%20delighted%20when%20a%20sharp-eyed%20reader%20charged%20him%20with%20copycatting%20the%20repeated%20refrain%20of%20%E2%80%9Cfalls%20the%20shadow%E2%80%9D%20in%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Hollow%20Men%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20from%20Ernest%20Dowson%E2%80%99s%20poem%2C%20%3Cem%3ECynara%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20about%20a%20lost%20love%3A%20%E2%80%9CThere%20fell%20thy%20shadow%2C%20Cynara!%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EFar%20from%20taking%20the%20reader%E2%80%99s%20comment%20as%20an%20accusation%20of%20plagiarism%2C%20or%20imitation%2C%20Eliot%20saw%20it%20as%20a%20vindication%20of%20his%20proposition%20of%20the%20passing%20on%20of%20the%20baton%20of%20literary%20tradition%20through%20successive%20inheritors%20of%20a%20common%20legacy.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ELess%20academically%2C%20but%20more%20amusingly%2C%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EAmerican%20comic%20Tom%20Lehrer%20did%20his%20own%20take%20on%20the%20subject%20of%20imitation%20and%20mimicry%20when%20he%20sang%3A%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%20%E2%80%9CPlagiarise%2C%20plagiarise%2C%20plagiarise!%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EWhy%20do%20you%20think%20God%20gave%20you%20eyes%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EBut%20to%20plagiarise%